x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In any case, Trump =
campaign sources are insistent that this week will be Harris=E2=80=99s high=
-water mark in the polls, and that after the expected convention bounce, th=
e race will start to equalize again. His campaign is already up with policy=
-focused advertising in the swing states, tying Harris to failures on immig=
ration and the economy. But out on the trail, Trump continues to give his a=
dvisors fits, attacking Harris for her appearance, intelligence, gender, an=
d race, and there=E2=80=99s a fear that once Trump sees the polls after the=
 convention, he=E2=80=99ll become even more reckless=E2=80=94doubling down =
on personal attacks and also lashing out at his own team. =E2=80=9CAs much =
as Trump says he dismisses public polling, he very much looks at it and get=
s upset by what he sees,=E2=80=9D said one of these sources. <br/><br/>Alas=
, as Trump weathers the indignity of a week of
sustained criticism from heavy hitters like the <b>Obamas</b> and the <b>Cl=
intons</b> at the D.N.C., I=E2=80=99m hearing that the advisors and senior =
campaign officials urging Trump to play nice are losing that argument. Inst=
ead, the emerging conventional wisdom is that Trump has earned the <i>right=
 </i>to personal attacks that satisfy his need to hit back, as long as they=
 are <i>actually</i> effective and don=E2=80=99t turn off independents and =
swing voters. =E2=80=9CHe feels like it=E2=80=99s a double standard,=E2=80=
=9D one advisor told me. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s not supposed to respond? Any=
one would.=E2=80=9D Another advisor disagreed with the need to accommodate =
Trump=E2=80=99s desire to counterpunch: =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t care about=
 being fair, I just want to win.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Next week, the campaign =
plans to try a new line of attack, focusing on the fact that Harris hasn=E2=
=80=99t held a press conference, suggesting that she=E2=80=99s hiding from =
reporters because she=E2=80=99s not quick on her feet. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=
=99ll just keep mocking her and attacking
her and trying to get reporters to ramp up the pressure,=E2=80=9D said a ca=
mpaign source. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99ll really hammer that coming out of [t=
he convention]. They think when she=E2=80=99s not on her script, that=E2=80=
=99s when she gets exposed.=E2=80=9D<b> Kellyanne Conway</b>, who hasn=E2=
=80=99t officially joined the campaign but is someone, like Lewandowski, Tr=
ump has been turning to for advice, told me, =E2=80=9CTrump can prevail aga=
inst Kamala on both policy and personality. Polls show he is preferred on t=
he economy, border, crime, and national security.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>And yet=
, perhaps the biggest coup for Trump will be getting <b>Robert F. Kennedy J=
r.</b>=E2=80=99s support tomorrow, when he=E2=80=99s expected to announce t=
he suspension of his campaign and endorse Trump, helping him solidify his g=
rip on the <b>Joe Rogan</b>-verse of anti-vaxxers and other low-propensity =
voters. I=E2=80=99m told that they=E2=80=99re currently working on the deta=
ils of Kennedy=E2=80=99s future role with the campaign, namely which region=
s they would deploy him
to and with what type of messaging. <b>Karl Rove</b> suggested on Fox News =
today that Kennedy could be useful in Arizona and Georgia, where he may hav=
e only 10,000 or so followers, but could push Trump over the edge in a coin=
 flip election. It=E2=80=99s unclear whether Kennedy=E2=80=99s running mate=
 <b>Nicole Shanahan</b>, who said on a podcast this week that R.F.K. would =
make a terrific secretary of Health and Human Services in a Trump administr=
ation, will campaign for Trump, herself. <br/></td>
